<TEXT>
the air force lacks an accurate accounting 
system similar to those in private industry that could forecast 
problems in its billions of dollars of weapons purchases according 
to a draft report by congressional investigators 
the washington post said in thursday editions that an early 
draft of the report said the air force had grossly understated 
the cost of major weapons systems by tens of billions of dollars 
over the past decade 
it said costs of frontline warplanes were understated by 27 
billion from 1975 to 1988 and 18 billion in unneeded equipment 
was purchased 
the air force is now spending about 14 billion a year buying 
aircraft of all kinds 
a source at the general accounting office whose analysts 
prepared the report said the severely critical comments of the 
draft obtained by the newspaper might have been toned down somewhat 
in later drafts 
in comments included in the report the air force largely 
concurs with the overall assessment by the gao investigators that 
its system has problems the gao source said speaking on condition 
on anonymity 
the newspaper quoted an air force statement as saying the report 
creates a faulty impression of waste and mismanagement 
the gao source said the document should not be taken to mean 
they dont have any financial control over systems purchases 
the report makes more than 20 recommendations to improve air 
force accounting 
charles bowsher comptroller general and head of the general 
accounting office has been worried that the governments 
accounting systems are out of date he chose to examine the air 
force system on the grounds that it is the best in the defense 
department the gao source said 
the report had been planned for transmittal to the senate 
government operations committee chaired by sen john glenn 
dohio on march 1 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

