<TEXT>
starting may 1 exxon will resume its 
cleanup of oil remaining in prince william sound and the gulf of 
alaska from the nations largest oil spill company officials said 
wednesday 
exxon suspended its cleanup in september because of the onset of 
severe winter weather but had declined to set a date for further 
work 
we know now that some additional work is going to be needed 
spokesman joe tucker said additional cleanup as required will 
begin around may 1 weather permitting 
exxon officials said survey teams found oil at a depth of 28 
inches in one site but at most problem areas the depth was about 4 
to 6 inches said hann jahns an exxon scientist 
the company found serious problems along about 10 of the 90 
miles of shoreline its crews surveyed jahns said 
the extent of the remaining work will not be determined until 
april tucker said but he predicted the 1990 cleanup would be 
substantially smaller than efforts carried out last year 
the tanker exxon valdez ran aground march 24 on bligh reef south 
of valdez spewing nearly 11 million gallons of north slope crude 
hundreds of miles of rocky shoreline were covered with oil and 
countless birds and sea mammals died 
following a meeting of 70 oilspill officials in anchorage on 
tuesday coast guard rear adm david ciancaglini announced that 
exxon would resume the cleanup 
ciancaglini said exxon was not ordered to return exxon will 
return because they are needed to do so he said 
exxon federal and state officials have agreed on a basic 
schedule for the spring cleanup tucker said the company will 
submit a general cleanup plan to ciancaglini by march 15 
ciancaglini the federal onscene coordinator for the cleanup 
said he will have to approve exxons plan before it is put into 
effect 
exxon the coast guard and state and federal agencies will 
develop the best strategy and decide on the appropriate methods to 
remove the remaining oil ciancaglini said 
the agencies and exxon have been working for weeks to assess how 
much oil has been removed by waves rain and other natural 
processes though they disagree on the exact amounts all say 
winter has had a major cleansing effect on the sound but they say 
some of the more protected areas are still in trouble 
ciancaglini said survey crews from exxon the state department 
of environmental conservation and other agencies would spend most 
of april surveying the shores they will meet in late april to 
develop cleanup strategies 
he praised exxons cooperation in assessing the cleanup needs 
with state and federal officials but he said he would not hesitate 
to order a federal takeover of the cleanup if exxon refused to 
carry out the work 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

