<TEXT>
here are key provisions of the contract 
approved by united mine workers in virginia west virginia and 
kentucky who have been on strike since april 5 against the pittston 
coal group 
term 4 years 
wages top scale of 1752 an hour in selected positions a 
raise of 120 an hour 
health benefits 100 percent medical coverage for employees 
pensioners and their families 
retirement pension benefits identical to the 1988 agreement 
between the umw and the bituminous coal operators association 
job security pittston can hire contract workers for 
transportation and equipment repair and maintenance if no union 
miners are laid off laidoff union miners must be hired for the 
first four of every five job openings at pittstons nonunion mines 
and providers of contract workers must agree to offer the first 19 
of every 20 jobs to laidoff union miners 
working hours flexible schedules including fourday weeks of 
10 hours each and 28day shift rotations which would allow almost 
roundtheclock operation of mines 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900221-0011 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
here is a list of significant events in the strike between the 
united mine workers union and pittston coal group inc 
may 19 1987 pittston said it would leave the bituminous coal 
operators association and negotiate independently with the umw 
beginning for a contract to replace the national contract expiring 
jan 31 1988 
april 5 1989 umw called a strike against pittston in virginia 
west virginia and kentucky for alleged unfair labor practices after 
union members worked 14 months without a contract 
april 12 umw members arrested for throwing rocks at company 
trucks in dickenson county the first of hundreds of violent acts 
designed to disrupt coal shipments and intimidate replacement 
workers 
april 27 more than 1000 umw members and supporters blocked two 
mines in a sitdown demonstration the beginning of a civil 
disobedience campaign that led to more than 2000 arrests in the 
first three months of the strike 
may 8 negotiations began through the federal mediation and 
conciliation service 
may 16 russell county circuit judge donald mcglothlin fined the 
umw 642000 for violating his order limiting strike activities and 
prohibiting the disruption of pittston operations mcglothlins 
fines eventually totalled 645 million 
june 5 us district judge glenn williams threw umw strike 
coordinators marty hudson and jackie stump in jail for contempt of 
court they were released two weeks later 
june 7 the union withdrew from federally mediated negotiations 
accusing pittston of bargaining in bad faith 
june 10 pittston declared an impasse in negotiations and 
implemented its final contract offer essentially saying take it or 
leave it 
june 11 umw president richard trumka promised to widen the 
strike the next day a series of wildcat strikes began that spread 
to the midwest and eventually had more than 46000 miners off the 
job in sympathy with the pittston strikers 
june 19 union members and supporters including wildcat 
strikers from other states began bumpertobumper convoys of 
several hundred cars and trucks to slow coal shipments the tactic 
ended a few weeks later after williams fined the union nearly 1 
million and began throwing drivers in jail for contempt of court 
july 8 the national labor relations board issued an unfair 
labor practices complaint against pittston 
july 18 umw and pittston agreed to resume federally mediated 
contract talks but could not agree to meet in the same room and 
negotiations failed to progress 
aug 23 trumka aflcio president lane kirkland and 19 
officials representing a dozen other unions arrested in a sitdown 
demonstration at the russell county va courthouse 
sept 17 ninetyeight striking miners and union officials 
launched an unarmed invasion of pittstons main processing and 
shipping plant in russell county and occupied it for four days 
while as many as 3000 supporters rallied outside 
oct 11 international labor leaders including representatives 
of the polish solidarity attended a rally of pittston strikers and 
took the strikers case to labor secretary elizabeth dole the next 
day in washington 
oct 13 dole visited striking miners and pittston workers and 
announced she would meet with trumka and pittston co chairman paul 
douglas for the two sides first facetoface meeting since june 
two weeks later dole appointed former labor secretary william 
usery to mediate 
nov 9 contract talks resumed with trumka and douglas at the 
table 
jan 1 dole trumka and douglas announced a tentative 
settlement and agreed to withhold a vote on it until all 
strikerelated litigation was dissolved 
feb 12 mcglothlin refused to drop the 64 million in fines 
two days later judge williams agreed to reduce his fines against 
