great britains prince charles told 
business leaders from around the globe tuesday that the world needs 
a new deal where capitalism takes on a more humane face 
the crucial factor is whether such an approach can be 
commercial and yet surely it must be good business in the long 
run the prince of wales told about 100 corporate executives 
gathered for an international business conference 
the prince arrived in charleston around noon and was warmly 
cheered by a crowd of about 200 people as he entered the old 
exchange building where south carolinians ratified the us 
constitution in 1788 
about 100 chief executive officers and top business officials 
are attending a twoday meeting of business in the community a 
londonbased group founded by the prince which brings corporate 
leaders together to discuss the roles and responsibilities of 
business 
business is at a crossroads charles told the conference 
does it enter new markets like the cowboys of the new frontier or 
does it take a rather more sophisticated approach which leads to 
continued rather than shortterm profit 
he suggested business leaders can neither take a shortterm 
approach in search of quick profits nor leave the larger problems 
of the environment and education only to the government 
there is no better illustration of this than the greatly 
increased concern by consumers about the impact of business 
processes and products upon the environment he said these are 
no longer frontier days when businesses can afford to make 
shortterm decisions 
the prince who will be in charleston through wednesday is 
making his second visit to the city once known as charles towne he 
last visited in 1977 
during a lunch with the business leaders the prince praised 
mayor joseph p riley jr for the mayors efforts to build the 
antebellum tourist city into an international asset 
charleston has ridden out disaster and setbacks over many 
years not just the terrifying recent effects and loss caused by 
hurricane hugo he said referring to the sept 21 storm that 
left 29 dead and 59 billion in damage in south carolina 
riley said the princes visit would focus attention on the fact 
that charleston has bounced back after the hurricane 
tuesday night the prince and about 400 people attended a 
blacktie gala to benefit hurricane victims 
about 100 people looked on as business leaders and a whos who 
of charleston society entered the brightly lit hibernian hall for 
an evening of dancing 
guests were asked to donate 100 each to the hurricane relief 
effort 
the prince is expected to attend several more conference 
sessions wednesday and visit a public housing complex he plans to 
leave thursday for washington for a meeting with president bush 
