<TEXT>
an opposition coalition glued together 
from an atomized fractious array of parties is posing the 
strongest challenge to the sandinistas rule since they took power 
more than a decade ago 
the united national opposition called uno now consists of 14 
parties or party factions all backing opposition newspaper 
publisher violeta barrios de chamorro a living symbol of the fight 
for democracy 
uno is spanish for one but the nicaraguan political tradition 
of uniting in the face of a common enemy seldom lasts long after 
defeat or victory 
president daniel ortega seeking reelection has tried to drive 
a wedge into the opposition coalition by mocking the wide variety 
of parties comprising uno they range from the communist party to 
ideological opposites in the conservative party 
this is such a mishmash it can give you indigestion 
ortega told delighted supporters at one rally let president 
bush eat it 
can uno hold together and govern through 1996 should it win 
sundays general elections 
yes we have matured alfredo cesar an adviser to mrs 
chamorro said in an interview 
he said one reason is we have a unanimously agreedto 
government program 
dona violeta is the second reason everyone in the coalition 
trusts she will comply with her commitment and put the program into 
place 
at least for now everyone has something to gain by sticking 
together and everything to lose if they let mutual suspicions drive 
them apart 
but when the hopedfor spoils were being divided at least one 
party was not happy 
the secretarygeneral of peoples social christian party stayed 
within uno while its president joined a social christian alliance 
running separately 
the official reason was irreconcilable differences the widely 
believed rumor was that the party president mauricio diaz did not 
think his party had been granted enough candidates for the 90 
national assembly seats at stake 
nicaraguas political cast is full of splinter parties besides 
ortega and mrs chamorro there are eight other presidential 
candidates 
unos vicepresidential candidate virgilio godoy of the 
independent liberal party has been criticized within the coalition 
as arrogant and abrasive 
the power struggle wont be settled by the voters because each 
party will be able to claim it was a major drawing card for mrs 
chamorros ticket 
nicaraguas past doesnt offer much of a model for stability 
said jorge eduardo arellano a history professor 
theres no history here theres only a caricature arellano 
said despite the idea of the liberals and conservatives 
traditionally dominating nicaraguan politics up to 10 factions 
existed at the turn of the century six in the 1940s he said 
the somozas who ran nicaragua from the time of the death of 
augusto cesar sandino in 1934 until they were toppled by sandinos 
heirs in 1979 were able to use the internal dynamics of coalitions 
to divide and rule 
the sandinistas themselves have displayed a party discipline 
that has proven their biggest strength 
thats the really amazing thing that the nine comandantes 
top party leaders have hung together for 10 years a western 
diplomat said 
nevertheless during their years as a guerrilla group the 
sandinistas split into three factions 
one advocated a prolonged guerrilla war another favored 
educating the masses on marxist theory and slowly building up urban 
discontent the third was intent on seizing the first opportunity 
to push a mass insurrection 
the third faction was able to forge tactical alliances with 
angry nicaraguans of all social classes to knock down somoza in 
july 1979 
despite that the sandinistas united to rule although there 
have been rumored disagreements notably over ending a ceasefire 
last november with the usbacked contra rebels 
the assassination of mrs chamorros husband pedro joaquin 
chamorro was the spark that lit the sandinista revolution and the 
winners initially forged a junta that included nonsandinistas 
including mrs chamorro 
the nonsandinistas didnt last long though 
since then the sandinistas have faced several opposition 
coalitions including the democratic coordinating board which 
eventually dropped out of the 1984 elections 
this time despite internal bickering fraying at the edges and 
gaping differences in background and thinking the main opposition 
coalition has managed to hang together at least through the 
campaign 
