the city council voted unanimously tuesday to 
take all possible steps to stop aerial pesticide spraying against 
the medfly heating up the dispute between rural and urban areas 
over how to fight the cropkilling insect 
disagreeing with official assurances the spraying is safe the 
council approved a motion to pursue lawsuits and administrative 
appeals to force the state to halt spraying and to study the 
potential risks of malathion 
this is going to be a tough case but its a case we have to 
fight said councilman joel wachs the public has a right and a 
demand to know if the goverment is leveling with them 
the council also voted 150 to look into blocking the movement 
of all produce through los angeles airport and harbor facilities 
until farm officials agree to discuss with the city the use of 
malathion 
councilwoman gloria molina said state officials have failed to 
look seriously at the possible risks of spraying because of 
pressure from the powerful agricultural industry 
the state is spraying 400 square miles of los angeles and orange 
counties at night to wipe out the worst infestation of the 
cropdestroying bug since 198182 helicopters drop a mixture of 
malathion and sticky corn syrup bait 
agriculture officials contend the spraying poses no health risks 
and is a necessary step to avert an estimated 200 million in crop 
losses a year if the medfly becomes established in the state 
the mediterranean fruit fly lays its eggs in more than 250 
varieties of fruits vegetables and nuts grown in california the 
crops are destroyed when the larvae hatch and eat their way out 
councilman michael woo called the spraying a blatant example 
of the urban population of this state being held hostage to the 
agricultural industry 
california farm bureau spokesman clark biggs said farmers 
sympathize with southern californians for having to live with the 
spraying but contended that wiping out the medfly is in everyones 
best interest 
