accounting office agreed that as little as 30 billion of the 
gross 87 billion total of accounts receivable may be collectible 
it is going to be tens of billions of dollars goldberg 
said whether its 30 billion or 40 billion its a lot of 
money he said the irs has to abandon efforts to collect up to 3 
billion each year because of a sixyear statute of limitations 
goldberg acknowledged the irs has no way of knowing how much can 
be collected or even why the delinquency figure continues to grow 
he said the irs will be able to cut into accounts receivable if 
congress approves the 50 million that president bush asked to add 
1000 personnel to the agencys 20000employee collection division 
next year he noted the irs has under way a longterm plan to 
modernize its computer systems 
goldberg and robert m tobias president of the national 
treasury employees union which represents most irs employees 
criticized the uponeyear downthenext spending for irs workers 
goldberg said about 25 billion of the 87 billion accounts 
receivable is considered currently not collectible and unlikely to 
be collected in the future an account is given this label when 
for example a corporation goes out of business or the irs 
determines an individual is unable to pay 
the remaining 62 billion involves about 13 million accounts 
receivable including 3300 that total more than 14 billion 
goldberg said 17 accounts totaling 54 billion involve at least 
100 million each much of the total is not collectible because it 
is bloated by duplications and by errors by the irs and taxpayers 
goldberg defended the irss record between 1984 and 1989 we 
collected over 5 trillion in revenue he noted our current 
accounts receivable inventory is less than 2 percent of that 
amount and we will ultimately collect most of what is due 
