<TEXT>
francis keppel a harvard university lecturer who 
was us commissioner of education under presidents kennedy and 
johnson died at the university at age 73 
keppel who died monday at harvards stillman infirmary was 
considered a leader in education he was commissioner of education 
from 1962 to 1966 and was dean of the ivy league schools graduate 
school of education from 1948 to 1962 
since 1974 keppel had been director of the educational policy 
program of the aspen institute and was an adviser to libraries art 
centers and the world bank 
keppel led the drive for passage of the elementary secondary 
education act of 1965 which focused resources on classroom 
assistance for poor children he was also closely involved in 
enforcing the civil rights act of 1964 as it applied to equal 
access to education and created was the national assessment of 
education progress 
harvard and the nation lose one of their great public servants 
with the death of frank keppel harvard president derek bok said 
in a statement he was a modest ethical man few can equal his 
lifelong dedication to improving education 
keppel received his ab degree from harvard in 1938 and 
studied sculpture for a year at the american academy in rome he 
resumed academic studies while serving as an assistant dean at 
harvard college from 1939 to 1941 
during world war ii he was secretary of the joint army and navy 
committee on welfare and recreation then joined the army rising 
from private to lieutenant he left the army in 1946 
two years later keppel became dean of the graduate school of 
education he promoted a master of arts in teaching program and 
other innovations in teaching 
keppel is survived by his wife edith sawin keppel of cambridge 
two daughters a brother and four grandchildren 
a mermorial service was to be held friday at the memorial church 
in harvard yard 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

