<TEXT>
the department of transportation says the risk 
of cancer among airline crew members from cosmic radiation is 
nearly 17 times greater than it reported last week 
the dot on tuesday acknowledged an error in a major study 
assessing airliner cabin environment officials said the error 
occurred when a researcher copied figures from the wrong table 
the report originally estimated that cosmic radiation could 
cause from 5 to 61 additional deaths from cancer per 100000 crew 
members flying for 20 years 
the revised figures put this at up to 1000 additional deaths 
per 100000 for crew members who fly long routes about twice a week 
and about 500 deaths per 100000 among passengers who fly long 
routes once a week 
these deaths would be in addition to the expectation that 22000 
out of 100000 about one out of five people will die of cancer 
from all causes 
officials cautioned however that the risk data is not based on 
any study of actual cancer cases but on mathematical models 
projecting the effects of lowlevel cosmic radiation based on what 
is known about higher radiation doses 
bob marx dot spokesman said officials are concerned about the 
radiation risk to airliner crews and the federal aviation 
administration plans to issue a warning document 
