<TEXT>
the yearold free trade agreement between the 
united states and canada is having little national impact on 
farmers according to an agriculture department report 
one reason is that the uscanada agreement was negotiated at 
the same time agriculture had the international spotlight in the 
uruguay round of the general agreement on tariffs and trade said 
alan webb of the departments economic research service 
the uscanada pact went into effect jan 1 1989 and was 
designed to remove all tariff and some nontariff barriers to 
agricultural trade between the two countries within 10 years 
the gatt talks probably caused both countries to restrain the 
scope of their bilateral agricultural negotiations webb said in 
the february issue of farmline magazine neither side wanted to 
make major concessions that would have reduced their bargaining 
chips in the larger multilateral gatt talks 
but the looming presence of gatt did help spur some progress on 
agriculture in the uscanada agreement largely because it would 
have appeared as bad form not to have some favorable results 
for two relatively friendly open countries to admit defeat on 
negotiating something on agriculture would have sent a bad signal 
to the international community particularly since both countries 
maintain that the real culprits in international agricultural trade 
are the european community and japan webb said 
canada and the united states have similarities in agricultural 
production and trade meaning there are few reasons to negotiate 
changes or opportunities for tradeoffs also he said agricultural 
trade with the united states and the freetrade agreement are 
far more important to canada than the other way around 
webb said the us view was that the small size of the canadian 
market did not justify large concessions 
the united states would not make major changes in its domestic 
agricultural policies particularly those which would affect 
headtohead competition with canada in other export markets on 
the basis of canadian concessions on agriculture he said 
but webb said that in the larger multilateral talks of the 
uruguay round significant changes in domestic policies are more 
likely 
