<TEXT>
an agriculture department report shows 1990 
farm income estimates are holding as predicted although there is 
some slippage from the record level of two years ago 
net cash income may be in the range of 52 billion to 57 
billion compared with an estimated 53 billion in 1989 and the 
record of 572 billion in 1988 the report said tuesday 
that is the money left over after deducting cash expenses from 
gross cash income during a calendar year it can include proceeds 
from sales of inventory commodities produced in previous years 
net farm income another method of bookkeeping may be in the 
range of 44 billion to 49 billion this year compared with 48 
billion in 1989 and 427 billion in 1988 
this method measures income from farming during a specific year 
including changes in the value of inventories allowances for 
family dwellings depreciation and other factors 
figures for both accounting methods were unchanged from 
projections made by the departments economic research service the 
last two months 
agriculture secretary clayton yeutter noted in testimony before 
the house agriculture committee earlier tuesday virtually all 
indicators of farm sector wellbeing have improved the last few 
years 
farm income is up farm failures are down farmland values are 
recovering and debttoasset ratios have improved yeutter said 
commodity surpluses have all but disappeared some idle land has 
returned to production and farm program spending is down 
the agency report said farmland values have been revised based 
on the 1987 census of agriculture the average us price of 
farmland as of february 1989 for example was revised upward to 
667 per acre from the earlier estimate of 597 no state figures 
were included 
