and france and in the conference on security and cooperation 
on south africa only portugal supported britains in arguing 
that an easing of sanctions was warranted by the lifting of some 
restrictions by south african president fw de klerk this month 
and the feb 11 release of black nationalist leader nelson mandela 
it is not enough to sit back and say thats encouraging 
lets see what you do next said hurd 
collins said the community view was that the reforms while 
welcome do not yet go far enough perhaps there is agreement 
that we could look at our policy again when the state of emergency 
is lifted and all political prisoners are released 
the community agreed to send a factfinding mission to south 
africa comprised of representatives from france ireland and italy 
hurd said the move would be interpreted as a signal of the twelve 
delaying rather than encouraging 
the new investment ban was one of a series of nonbinding 
measures the community agreed to in 1986 
britain has long opposed sanctions and now argues that its 
policy of seeking to encourage south africas whiteled government 
to move way from apartheid has helped push de klerk into reform 
most other countries say he has moved because of the pressure of 
sanctions and resistance by the black majority which is denied a 
vote in national affairs by apatheid 
mrs thatcher is already under attack for what critics say is 
compromising british influence internationally by being out of step 
on south africa and being hesitant about german unification 
hurd indicated tuesday that president bush supports the british 
view that de klerk deserves a response from the international 
community 
