<TEXT>
amnesty international said today that 
communist vietnam is still convicting people in unfair trials 
cutting food rations for some prisoners and putting some in 
solitary confinement or shackles 
the londonbased human rights group said vietnam has undertaken 
major human rights reforms since pragmatists took over the 
communist party leadership in december 1986 but many of the 
measures have not yet been implemented 
new legislation provides for development of an independent 
judiciary and contains such principles as the presumption of 
innocence the right not to be detained without a court order the 
right to legal defense and to choose an independent lawyer said 
the report released today 
however many of the reforms intended to protect specific 
human rights have not been implemented and human rights violations 
continue it said 
many western governments and human rights groups have accused 
hanoi of widespread human rights violations since north vietnamese 
forces defeated the usbacked south vietnam government in april 
1975 
the government told an amnesty delegation that visited vietnam 
last may that it was committed to renovation in all fields and 
stressed the importance of the rule of law the report said 
a copy of the report vietnam renovation doi moi the law 
and human rights in the 1980s was received in bangkok doi moi 
is the vietnamese term for renovation 
the 66page study said reports of abuses of detainees suggest 
that these practices are still common and that measures to combat 
them are not yet adequate 
abusive treatment in reeducation camps includes the use of 
solitary confinment in combination with beatings the use of 
shackles or leg irons and the reduction of food rations it said 
the report welcomed the release of thousands of people under 
government amnesties in 1987 and 1988 including more than 1500 
political prisoners detained without charge or trial in 
reeducation camps since the end of the war 
it said hanoi has told amnesty it soon will free the remaining 
130 former south vietnam government and military personnel arrested 
just after the war 
but it added that hanoi has not said anything about the many 
political prisoners detained more recently who had no connection 
with the former government 
among prisoners of conscience convicted in unfair trials have 
been buddhist monks jesuit priests protestant pastors writers 
and others believed to have been convicted solely because they were 
critical of government policies it said 
the report said the 1989 criminal code procedure contains no 
provision for detention without trial and appears to make such 
detention for reeducation illegal but the norms of the procedure 
have not been comprehensively implemented it said 
amnesty also expressed concern over the broad definition of 
crimes against national security in the code and said this has 
been used to convict prisoners of conscience in unfair trials 
the report said prisoners of conscience include poet and writer 
nguyen chi thien who has spent more than half his life in 
detention he is believed still under detention since he was 
arrested for the third time in 1979 it said 
