<TEXT>
production of plutonium triggers for nuclear 
warheads at the rocky flats plant in colorado may not resume 
completely before late summer a senior energy department official 
said today 
production was suspended indefinitely late last year to allow 
egampg inc which runs the plant under an energy department 
contract to install new safety and management practices the plant 
is the only source of plutonium triggers and is considered a vital 
link in the us nuclear weapons production chain 
adm jm barr a top adviser to energy secretary james d 
watkins on nuclear arms production said no firm target date had 
been set for resuming production but that rocky flats was expected 
to be in full swing sometime between july and september 
watkins had said shortly after the shutdown that he hoped 
production could resume by february 
speaking to a reporter during a break in a meeting with a 
department advisory committee barr said watkins now hoped to get 
the first plutonium processing facility known as building 771 
back in operation by june at the latest five other buildings at 
the site near denver also are involved in plutonium processing 
barr told the advisory committee on nuclear facility safety 
which is monitoring efforts to get rocky flats back in operation 
that by early april he would offer a specific target date for full 
resumption of plutonium trigger production 
were afraid anything we would give you now would be wrong 
he told the panel 
rocky flats has been plagued by a variety of operating and waste 
handling problems in recent years last june the fbi raided the 
facility in search of evidence of criminal violations of laws 
governing the handling of radioactive waste rockwell international 
corp quit as rocky flats operator last september 
barr told the advisory committee that the top objective of 
egampgs overhaul of rocky flats operations is to improve the 
margin of safety he stressed however that there was no 
imminent danger to the public from rocky flats operations last fall 
dave van leuven egampgs associate general manager for defense 
production at rocky flats outlined for the committee the tasks to 
be completed before production resumes he said for example that 
more than 1000 engineering drawings of safety systems would be 
checked for accuracy about 150 of the drawings have been checked 
already he said and it will take another eight weeks to do the 
rest 
van leuven said the technical competence of about 1500 plant 
operators would be verified before production is resumed he did 
not say how many already have been tested but he said the failure 
rate so far was about 30 percent 
egampg a massachusettsbased private technology company runs 
several energy department nuclear facilities 
