<TEXT>
legislators got their first look today at a draft 
of proposed constitutional changes that would strengthen the post 
of the presidency now held by mikhail s gorbachev 
vladimir tumanov an official at the institute of state and law 
in moscow who helped prepare the draft said copies were 
distributed to members of the supreme soviet the national 
legislature which held closed committee meetings today he said he 
had not seen the draft and could not give details 
gorbachev has appealed to the supreme soviet to approve his plan 
for a westernstyle presidential system 
the washington post reported today that copies of the proposed 
changes have circulated in the kremlin it said that the changes 
would among other things provide for the president to be elected 
to sixyear terms and give him veto power 
the new york times today also carried a story on the proposed 
changes it quoted legislators who have seen the draft as saying 
the plan would include creation of a strengthened presidency this 
spring and the immediate selection of the president by the national 
parliament 
sergei stankevich a progressive member of a parliamentary 
commission that considers draft laws submitted to the supreme 
soviet said the changes would give the soviet president most of 
the powers of his french and american counterparts without many of 
their constitutional limitations the post said 
however deputies from the northern baltic states are alarmed 
over provisions that impose severe restrictions on the rights of 
republics to secede and permit authorities to crack down on 
nationalist organizations 
i dont think this new legislation will be acceptable to 
anyone who believes in a constitutional system of checks and 
balances stankevich told the newspaper 
alexander yakovlev a key gorbachev aide said the presidential 
system was necessary to ensure the stable development of a 
democracy in the soviet union 
deputies who have read the proposed changes told the post the 
draft includes the following points 
a sixyear presidential term with the first president elected 
by the 2250seat congress of peoples deputies the parent body of 
the supreme soviet subsequent presidents would be elected by 
universal suffrage 
the times said the president would be elected to fiveyear term 
it said a nationwide direct vote would not be held the first time 
because the feeling is that the country now cannot afford the time 
required to plan such a vote 
the president would have the right to veto legislation adopted 
by the supreme soviet a presidential veto could be overridden by a 
majority in both houses of the supreme soviet 
the president could declare a state of emergency in any region 
without securing the consent of the relevant republic 
the president would have wide powers to rule by decree when the 
supreme soviet is not in session 
the president would have the right to cancel legislation 
adopted by the parliaments of constituent republics 
the times said the changes would give the parliament the right 
to conduct a vote of noconfidence in the presidents government 
and that if the president lost he could disband parliament and call 
new elections 
the post said the draft could be submitted by the end of this 
month or the beginning of march to the 542member supreme soviet 
the congress of peoples deputies the supreme state body would 
have to approve any constitutional changes 
