the moves came as a dispute began between environment and 
agriculture officials over widespread pollution of drinking water 
due to drought heavy use of nitratebased fertilizers and recent 
floods 
the societe generale des eaux minerales de vittel announced it 
would withdraw from sale an estimated 1 million to 2 million 
bottles of hepar mineral water to allay consumer worries some might 
be contaminated with traces of hydrocarbons of the alkane type 
the underground springwater is distributed and consumed almost 
exclusively in france director alain dorfner told the associated 
press the company also produces the popular vittel water for 
domestic and foreign consumption 
supplies of hepar were contaminated jan 1011 when water 
sitting in a tank awaiting bottling came into contact with a filter 
exposed to air polluted with alkane dorfner said 
alkanes are a class of hydocarbon compounds including methane 
or ethane they occur naturally in some types of petroleum 
the water was bottled and shipped to points in france in 
january dorfner said and later quietly withdrawn from sale after 
the company discovered the contamination 
but the global recall of perrier water after a us laboratory 
found traces of benzene in some samples put the spotlight on hepar 
casting doubts on the waters purity 
the water now on the shelves is pure but we want to avoid 
confusion in peoples minds dorfner said new bottles will be 
on the shelves in 15 days 
