federal safety officials investigating the 
crash of an avianca jetliner in new york issued emergency 
recommendations today aimed at clarifying how pilots should declare 
fuel emergencies 
seventythree people died when the fuelstarved airliner crashed 
in long island while on approach to kennedy international airport 
in new york 
the national transportation safety board urged the federal 
aviation administration to alert all air carriers with flights in 
the united states that their crews must be thoroughly 
knowledgeable about faa rules including specific phrases to be 
used when a plane is running out of fuel 
the board with three of its four members concurring also 
called on the faa to issue a general notice to air traffic 
controllers on the circumstances of the jan 25 crash of the 
colombian airliner and to emphasize the need for controllers to 
request clarification of unclear or ambiguous transmissions 
from airliners that may convey an emergency 
pilots of the flight from bogota and medellin colombia told 
controllers several times they were running out of fuel 
however they never declared a formal minimum fuel status or 
emergency fuel condition which would have alerted controllers 
to clear them for landing as quickly as possible ntsb members said 
the board said it was continuing investigation into the cause of 
the crash and has not concluded that any specific communication 
or coordination problems were causal to the accident 
the faa is not required to adopt recommendations by the ntsb an 
independent agency 
