<TEXT>
some workers at the sellafield 
nuclear reprocessing plant may be counseled not to have children 
because higherthanexpected rates of leukemia have been found 
among workers children a company official said wednesday 
dr roger berry health and safety director for british nuclear 
fuels ltd operator of the plant said workers who want 
individual counseling can get it and if they are so worried the 
advice could be dont have children it is not something 
however that i hope would be widespread advice 
british nuclear fuels later issued a statement saying advising 
workers not to have families is not company policy 
a research team headed by martin gardner professor of medical 
studies at the university of southampton reported in last weeks 
british medical journal that children of men who worked at the 
plant had a higherthanexpected rate of leukemia 
british nuclear fuels said the company had promised medical 
counseling for all employees to ensure they understood the report 
and the risks to them if its findings are confirmed ultimately 
it is then for each individual worker to reach a decision not for 
the company to advise on one course of action or another it said 
gardner met with workers at the plant in northern england on 
wednesday and later said he was urging british nuclear fuels to 
study whether it was possible to minimize radiation exposures of 
younger workers 
these would be the sort of people who were still capable of 
having families and may prefer not working in higher radiation 
levels said gardner adding he did not wish to overstate the 
risks involved 
the risk of a child in this country getting leukemia is 1 in 
2000 while those whose fathers were exposed to the highest 
radiation levels is about 7 in 2000 or 1 in 300 
what i am saying to them is that 299 out of 300 children will 
not get leukemia even if their fathers have been subjected to the 
highest exposure levels 
gardner said he told workers his report did not prove a 
connection between childhood leukemia and radiation exposure to the 
fathers 
it is something that i suggest could be associated and not 
necessarily showing cause and effect he said 
alan johnson director of reprocessing at sellafield said he 
wanted to see more studies on possible links between leukemia and 
radiation 
we have always reduced radiation levels over the past 20 years 
and will continue to reduce them he said 
bernard owen a local official of the general and municipal 
boilermakers union said that as a matter of urgency we want to 
see a followup of his study and the collating of further studies 
into the problem before we can come to a firm conclusion 
martin forwood campaign secretary of core cumbrians opposed 
to a radioactive environment said he hoped wednesdays meetings 
would calm workforce fears 
publicly the workers may not state their worries because they 
are a very loyal and captive work force forwood said 
however i am sure that behind closed doors there must be a 
lot of doubt and concern among them especially among those of the 
reproductive age 
gardners study examined 52 victims of leukemia and lymphoma 
under 25 years old born in the west cumbria health district and 
diagnosed between 195085 they were compared with 1001 control 
children 
one researcher radiotherapist michael snee said the radiation 
probably caused a mutation in the fathers sperm 
in november the medical research council and the imperial 
research fund reported that an increased risk of leukemia is not 
associated with exposure to radiation with the possible exception 
of the sellafield plant which has been plagued by radiation leaks 
gardner said the main finding of his study was that the risk was 
highest for a father who received total exposure exceeding 100 
millisieverts one millisievert equals half a typical individuals 
annual dose from natural radiation or 50 times the dose of a 
single chest xray 
</TEXT>
