<TEXT>
attorney general dick thornburgh approved the 
partial merger of the two daily newspapers in york pa wednesday 
under the antitrust exemption of the newspaper preservation act 
thornburgh accepting the recommendation of the justice 
departments antitrust division approved the plan to merge the 
production and commercial operations of the morning york daily 
record and the evening york dispatch 
thornburgh found that the record qualified for a limited 
antitrust exemption as a failing newspaper because it lagged 
the dispatch in both circulation and advertising revenue 
this record reveals no plausible method by which the record 
could maintain its competitive position and its current revenues 
while continuing to defer longdelayed capital expenditures 
thornburgh said in his opinion 
thornburgh said there did not appear be any alternatives to a 
joint operating agreement that would allow the record to remain 
financially as well as editorially independent of the dispatch 
the record owned by buckner news alliance has a circulation of 
40408 weekdays and 38328 on sundays according to 1988 figures 
that year the dispatch owned by garden state newspapers inc had 
a weekday circulation of 48310 and the companys sunday news had 
a circulation of 42482 
under the joint operating agreement the newspapers will 
maintain separate reporting staffs and publish separate editions 
during the week the record will discontinue its sunday edition but 
will produce its own comment section for insertion into the sunday 
news 
the dispatch will discontinue its saturday afternoon edition 
