<TEXT>
conservation officials on wednesday said 
they will crack down on desert poachers who smuggle rare animal and 
bird species out of oman for sale 
offenders will face sixmonth jail sentences and fines of up 
to 900 rials for contravening environmental laws conservation 
department spokesman yousuf albaloushi said the fine is 
equivalent to 2320 
he said the action follows the jailing in december of four omani 
tribesmen caught trucking arabian gazelles over the united arab 
emirates border they were convicted under environmental 
legislation banning the hunting of endangered species and are 
serving sixmonth jail terms baloushi said 
he added we believe they were part of an organized gang 
operating in the desert investigations are presently under way to 
find out exactly what has been going on 
baloushi said other prime targets included the nubian ibex and 
the houbara bird known biologically as the macqueens bustard a 
resident breeder the size of a goose 
poachers catch them live and export them to neighboring 
countries where they fetch a good price he said 
it appears there is a ready market for rare species like 
gazelles which are said to fetch around 500 rials 1300 apiece 
for private zoos baloushi said 
he said the arabian white oryx was not threatened this beast 
was extinct in the wild until it was reintroduced to the stony oman 
central desert preserve at yalooni in the jiddat al harasis 
the range wardens in the jiddat are active and the oryx are 
well guarded and protected elsewhere though we are bolstering 
our conservation patrol efforts baloushi said 
if we do not act now it will be too late we are talking here 
about species of animal and bird that are almost extinct existing 
only in oman it is a lobal issue in that respect 
government notices published in the local press on the orders 
of omans ruler sultan qaboos warned that the hunting of rare 
birds deer and other wildlife was prohibited 
the notices said police would maintain strict border 
surveillance to apprehend violators 
