<TEXT>
the office of management and budget may not 
block or change government regulations through its power to reduce 
paperwork requirements for private businesses the supreme court 
ruled wednesday 
the decision a victory for labor unions means that employers 
at certain multiemployer job sites must obey rules of the 
occupational safety and health administration requiring notice to 
workers of the dangers of certain consumer products used on the job 
the ombs power over government regulations has been contested 
by congressional committees and advocacy groups especially 
environmentalists for several years but the court said it was not 
ruling on their broad concerns only omb actions under the 
paperwork reduction act of 1980 
on a 72 vote the court held that the act does not give omb 
the authority to review agency rules mandating disclosure by 
regulated entities to third parties in the words of the majority 
opinion by justice william j brennan 
brennan said the court was leaving undecided whether other rules 
might legitimately be subject to omb review 
the dissenters chief justice william h rehnquist and justice 
byron r white dissented said the court should defer to ombs 
interpretation of the law 
the rules at issue were adopted by the occupational safety and 
health administration in 1983 to inform workers about the dangers 
of being exposed to hazardous materials 
the omb an arm of the white house objected four years later 
saying the multiemployer rules were unnecessary to protect 
employees and merely added to employers paperwork 
the united steelworkers union and others sued over the omb 
action and the philadelphiabased 3rd us circuit court of 
appeals ruled that the omb lacked the power to order a substantive 
change in another agencys rules 
wednesdays decision upheld the 3rd circuit ruling 
the justices last may refused to hear appeals by the 
construction and feed grain industries that objected coming under 
regulations for disclosing information on hazardous materials to 
workers 
the 1983 rules originally were imposed only on manufacturers 
but the federal government later was ordered to extend the rules to 
nonmanufacturing businesses 
in 1981 president reagan issued an executive order expanding an 
earlier order by president carter giving omb the power to review 
agency regulations which have the force of law 
reagans order gives omb to the extent not forbidden by law or 
court decisions the power to hold up regulations until agencies 
satisfy omb analysts that what they propose to do will be the most 
costeffective course possible 
in the reagan administration advocacy groups charged the omb 
frequently went beyond its mandate in imposing its views 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

