ambitious redevelopment of the beach followed and the beach 
population has become younger and less jewish in the last decade 
up to 40 percent of the new residents have been hispanic and the 
median age has dropped from 67 in 1982 to the low 50s 
resnick now 65 has lived in miami beach since 1960 
it was a very interesting life for jewish people he said 
there was everything catering to this type of life cultural 
events theaters people gathering to speak yiddish together the 
synagogues used to be so crowded they had to bring in chairs 
sheskin whos working on a history of jews in south florida 
noted the irony of the latin influx causing jews to leave an area 
that in the 1930s and 40s had antisemitic traditions hotels had 
restricted clientele and some restaurants posted cruel signs 
no jews or dogs 
new yorkraised soldiers stationed in the area during world war 
ii fell in love with the beach and began the huge migration here 
from the northeast along with european jews drawn to a land of 
sun sand and fun 
in 1940 there were 8000 jews in dade county sheskin said by 
1950 there were 55000 and in 1955 the number reached 100000 
but the jet age opening up destinations in the caribbean and 
south dulled some of the beachs glamour and the advent of 
planned condominium retirement communities began siphoning away its 
population 
many retirees simply died off or were priced out by the 
redevelopment that lured the young urban professionals discovering 
trendiness in the funky art deco buildings and a chance to live 
near the water 
the beach that once featured manhattan or las vegasstyle 
nightclub acts now is dotted with youth spots such as club nu or 
penrods on the beach offering lambada nights or rock bands 
three of 10 synagogues on south beach have closed in recent 
years and kosher butchers and jewish bookstores have moved north 
little by little its disappearing resnick said 
at torah treasures there still is good business for editions of 
the talmud israeli newspapers menorahs cassettes such as 
mordechai ben david singing moshiach is coming soon and treats 
for children such as rabbi trading cards mitsvah gum and the board 
game kosherland modeled after candyland 
but coowner aryeh zak here for 15 years said the changes on 
the street are many people use his backdoor as a toilet criminals 
plague him and in general people are not as friendly or polite 
zak said but i think thats a change all over he said 
many of his customers no longer live within walking distance 
but come from the broward and palm beach county suburbs now home to 
most of south floridas jews 
while the shift from south beach has been dramatic the overall 
jewish population in south florida has been increasing sheskin 
said some 650000 jews live in the threecounty palm 
beachbrowarddade area today he said compared to 550000 in 1980 
they represent 17 percent of the threecounty population more 
than the new york area with 12 percent or 22 million jews 
making up the nations mostconcentrated jewish population some of 
the latins are jewish too and sheskin estimates about 10000 
cuban jews or jewbans as theyre called live in south 
florida 
and miami beach still attracts new jewish migrants although 
many familes settle in whats known as middle beach north of 
41st street 
i see a rebirth of miami beach in the sense that so many young 
people and families are moving in said rabbi irving lehrman of 
temple emanuel weve lost a lot of people who passed away but 
weve gained a lot of young people 
if the beach loses its jewish identity its not a tragedy some 
say 
theres nothing sacred about south beach said rabbi tibor 
stern preparing to move his synagogue after 25 years to a 
community to the north its not jerusalem 
