<TEXT>
outside this drowsy town a 
hodgepodge of huts overgrown with rambling purple creepers is all 
thats left of the camp of slow death once the most feared 
prison of portugals african empire 
in those days it housed hundreds of portuguese and african 
dissidents in a myriad of cramped cells 
but todays independent government would like to turn it into a 
museum with beachside bungalows nearby to attract tourists and 
their money to this barren 10island archipelago in the atlantic 
off northwest africa 
it is part of cape verdes turn off the marxistsocialist road 
taken after independence in 1975 into freemarket square 
cape verdes leaders have introduced sweeping economic reforms 
and are even debating scrapping their guaranteed monopoly on power 
we have no abstract model no preconceived ideas prime 
minister pedro pires said sitting in his modest office in cidade 
da praia the capital were trying a pragmatic and gradual 
search for a better life 
the search includes tourism fishing and light manufacturing 
and perhaps investment from cape verdeans who emigrated over the 
years and now live in affluence in such places as the us east 
coast 
the governing african party for cape verdian independence 
decided just over a year ago to remove state controls from all 
sectors save the central bank and offer tax breaks to attract 
foreign capital 
the economy has been prudently managed but the only avenue 
out of chronic dependency is to become a sort of singapore or 
mauritius said tom luche director of us agency for 
international development in cidade da praia singapore and 
mauritius are dutyfree zones 
this place is small and theres a considerable amount of 
private cash here it only needs a couple of sectors to work 
well 
luche estimates cape verdes fishermen could triple their 
current 10000ton annual catch and improve canning and freezing 
installations for tuna and other fish which already account for 
about 70 percent of exports 
in addition to tarrafal another tourist prospect is sal island 
120 miles to the north where stready winds potent rum and cheap 
lobster already attract the ritzy european windsurfing set 
the government plans 10 new luxury hotels in the islands over 
the next 10 years boosting capacity by 2500 rooms 
but island life remains tough for most of the 360000 cape 
verdians who still live here 385 miles off senegal in africas 
sahel region 
with few natural resources other than rich fishing waters the 
archipelago relies on foreign aid for 90 percent of its food 
requirements 
famine killed an estimated 250000 islanders from 1747 to 1960 
and violent storms that ended a 16year dry period in 1984 washed 
out corn and wheat crops 
last year when rain fell for only minutes vegetables were so 
scarce that onions were sold by the slice and fetched twice the 
price of lobster 
most rural housewives have miles to walk for water their neat 
pastelpainted houses have no electricity 
still cape verdes per capita gross national product of 530 
lands it in the world banks middleincome class comparable to 
senegal and one rung up the development ladder from countries like 
kenya and indonesia 
but gnp is propped some 30 percent by foreign aid and 
remittances from an estimated 700000 cape verdians living and 
working abroad mainly on the us east coast portugal france 
the netherlands and several african countries 
in the 1800s many cape verde whalers settled in massachusetts 
and rhode island where today they number more than 350000 
they read their own newspaper the cape verdian and send 
money and goods regularly to families and friends back home 
were still not in condition to stop emigration but more and 
more emigrants are investing here following the new regulations 
said president aristides pereira 
besides financial incentives designed to tap exiles cash 
resources the government is also wooing them with talk of 
political pluralism 
next year independent candidates will be allowed to run in the 
firstever nationwide municipal vote 
we dont exclude the possibility of various parties but it 
really wasnt necessary until now a genuine pluralism of ideas 
exists within the party already said pereira who enjoys 
widespread popular support 
