<TEXT>
many parents who must reckon with the socalled 
kiddie tax have a new choice in how they handle it when they 
file their returns for 1989 
they can as before complete separate federal income tax 
returns for each of their offspring who must file or in some 
cases they may be allowed for the first time to incorporate the 
childrens income on their own tax returns 
the difference may sound like no big deal the main intent of 
the change was to make filing a little easier by eliminating the 
need for separate returns from children in relatively simple 
circumstances 
but experts on the subject say a decision for either option 
should be made with care since it could affect a familys overall 
tax bill 
the kiddie tax was born with the 1986 tax reform law which 
sought to curtail the popular practice of reducing taxes by 
shifting income to children and other dependents 
henceforth the law decreed investment income received by 
youngsters under age 14 would be taxed at their parents tax rate 
once it exceeded specified limits 
this immediately transformed a good many small children into 
fullblown socialsecuritycardcarrying taxpayers it turned out 
however that hardly anybody not even the internal revenue 
service was entirely happy about all the extra paperwork 
engendered by the change 
so was born the new option for parents of a child under 14 who 
has income of between 500 and 5000 derived entirely from 
interest and dividends on which no estimated tax or withholding 
has been paid 
whichever filing method you choose a child in this situation 
owes no tax on the first 500 of earnings the next 500 is taxed 
at a 15 percent rate 
past 1000 the money is taxed at the parents top rate which 
in many cases is 28 percent 
if sheer convenience were the only influencing factor a parent 
might logically prefer the election not to file a separate return 
for the child 
but as specialists on tax matters point out there may be other 
considerations that tip the scales either way 
for one thing including the income on your own return prevents 
you from deducting any expenses that children could claim if they 
filed separately 
conversely says the accounting firm of kmpg peat marwick by 
including your childs investment income on your return you may be 
able to deduct more investment interest expense because of your 
childs investment income this could effectively shelter a portion 
of your childs income from tax 
in addition lumping childrens income with parents can create 
complications for highincome taxpayers who may be subject to the 
alternative minimum tax 
still another possible side effect including your childs 
income on your return may also increase your adjusted gross income 
for purposes of the medical and miscellaneous itemized 
deductions cautions price waterhouse in the current edition of 
its book personal tax advisor 
medical costs and miscellaneous expenses for such things as 
professional dues and uniforms you buy can be deducted only when 
they exceed specified percentages of your gross income 
so if you increase your gross income by including what the child 
earned you may reduce the medical or miscellaneous deductions you 
can take 
</TEXT>
