<TEXT>
the rev j dean brackley was surprised at how 
deeply the murders of six jesuit priests in el salvador shook him 
up 
for a couple of days i was disoriented said the theology 
professor at fordham university then somebody snapped me out of 
it you know some good is going to come out of this 
brackleys response was to become one of more than 20 jesuits 
from throughout the world to volunteer to replace their slain 
colleagues at the jose simeon canas central american university he 
and five other priests from ireland canada mexico and spain have 
been assigned to the salvadoran university and more may be sent 
over 
we feel the support of the whole society said the rev 
carlos cabarrus of the loyola novitiate in panama city 
six priests their housekeeper and her teenage daughter were 
dragged out of their beds on the night of nov 16 and fatally shot 
by uniformed men the director of el salvadors military college 
and eight other soldiers were charged with the murders 
in the aftermath of the killings a lot of jesuits volunteered 
from all over the world to go to salvador to keep the university 
going said the rev richard buhler executive secretary of the 
us jesuit conference in washington 
the blood of martyrs becomes the seed of christians he said 
cabarrus said jesuit officials in central america are evaluating 
the applications of at least 20 jesuit volunteers from other parts 
of the world he said not all the applicants would be selected 
because of problems with obtaining visas and matching skills with 
needs 
the rev joseph ohare president of fordham university and 
chairman of the association of jesuit colleges and universities 
said following a recent threeday visit that the volunteers were 
appreciated by their salvadoran brethren 
one of the things they told us was that the murders had really 
been a devastating blow to them ohare said they really felt 
terribly isolated and alone 
if past experience is a guide the violence will serve only to 
strengthen the religious order cabarrus said 
he said the school for religious novices was started in 1975 
with 10 students and began to experience a substantial increase in 
membership after the murder of el salvador archbishop oscar romero 
in 1980 the twoyear program now has 34 novices the largest in 
the central american provinces history 
cabarrus said it is too early to tell how central american youth 
will react to the recent murders but i hope it will be great for 
us in vocations 
he said none of the current novices have dropped out just the 
opposite they are very encouraged by seeing the witnesses of those 
jesuits who were assassinated 
at the university cabarrus said there is fear of further 
violence among some of the lay faculty members but not at the 
level of students and not for the jesuits of course 
brackley who did pastoral work in el salvador in 1984 and 1988 
said he does not deny there is danger but having worked most of 
the last 10 years in the south bronx in new york has helped him 
live with insecurity 
i dont want to be a martyr and i dont think i will be he 
said 
without sounding too irish about the whole thing brackley 
said he preferred a life of adventure to bordeom 
there are few higher dramas in the world of religion than in el 
salvador brackley said 
its a drama of dying and rising he said on the one 
hand dying and suffering on the other hand great hope 
</TEXT>
