<TEXT>
the past seven months have seen rapid change in 
south africas apartheid the system imposed more than 40 years 
ago to keep the races apart an associated press correspondent who 
has watched the changes from his base in johannesburg looks at 
where apartheid stands now 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
miracles are happening 
said olga lutu who runs a school in a black shantytown freedom 
is a real possibility 
she was looking into the future 
so in his way was tj ferreira a 39yearold white service 
station owner 
i played sports with blacks and that didnt bother me he 
said i didnt mind lunching with blacks we just dont want to 
be governed by them 
apartheid while not dead is showing symptoms of terminal 
illness and the question before south africa now seems to be 
whether it will die a peaceful or painful death 
growing numbers of south africans across the political spectrum 
from black activists to rightwing whites believe the last of 
the major apartheid laws imposed in 1948 may be scrapped or 
rendered ineffective within a year or two possibly within months 
however sweeping the legal changes apartheid will leave a 
legacy of mistrust prejudice and economic inequality that may take 
decades to overcome 
but longterm worries are now coupled with a surge of optimism 
among blacks following president fw de klerks decision to free 
african national congress leader nelson mandela and lift a 30year 
ban on his organization 
everybody came out of their houses when we heard the news and 
we were singing in the streets said mrs lutu a robust 
energetic mother of four whose school is in a shantytown called 
orange farms 
she believes statutory apartheid will be gone within a few 
years a result of blacks increasing willingness to challenge the 
laws and the national party governments increasing reluctance to 
counter with repression 
the people are liberating themselves she said nothing 
ever happens if people are quiet 
apartheid has been crumbling slowly but steadily for more than a 
decade socalled petty apartheid segregation of theaters 
beaches and buses among other things has ended in most areas 
and rural blacks no longer face legal barriers if they want to move 
to a city 
de klerk has speeded up the pace of reform during his seven 
months in office asserting that discrimination is wrong and 
proposing negotiations aimed at extending political rights to 
blacks black militants are using their new maneuvering room to 
press for abolition of the last crucial group of laws known as the 
pillars of apartheid 
these include the group areas act which mandates segregation of 
residential areas the land act which prevents blacks from owning 
land in more than 80 percent of south africa and the population 
registration act which requires all south africans to be 
officially classified by race 
these laws have enabled the government to exclude blacks from 
national elections and persist with the last major categories of 
segregation residential areas staterun schools and public 
hospitals 
service station owner ferreira an afrikaner and a member of the 
proapartheid conservative party serves on the municipal council 
in boksburg an industrial city near johannesburg he and other 
conservatives took control of the council in 1988 and reinstituted 
whitesonly policies at recently integrated municipal 
facilities 
ferreira an outgoing man with a closeknit family holds de 
klerk as a traitor to the afrikaner people 
he said white conservatives were prepared to fight or secede 
into an allwhite homeland if the government surrendered power to 
blacks 
if blacks moved into his comfortable middleclass neighborhood 
he said theyll want whats ours a group might decide they 
like my house theyll come in and take it 
he expressed deep concern as well about the prospect of blacks 
entering whitesonly schools 
once that happens there will be fights among the kids most 
of our children have grown up wanting to be with their own 
people he said and whose standard of education do we adopt 
the blacks are so far behind in evolution theyll never catch up 
but theuns eloff a 34yearold afrikaner who has worked closely 
with ancaligned groups is happy with the way de klerk is handling 
things 
the national party has put into motion an irreversible process 
which within at the latest five years will erode its power base 
totally he said 
apartheid is finished 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900221-0228 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
eloff was reared in a loyal national party family and became a 
minister in the same branch of the dutch reformed church to which 
de klerk belongs but he quit this job and became a racerelations 
consultant after church leaders criticized him for antiapartheid 
political activities that included participation in a 1987 meeting 
with the anc 
eloff says de klerks moves took him and other liberal 
afrikaners by surprise he is now convinced the government will 
remove the remaining apartheid laws and yield political power if 
the anc provides some sort of guarantees for minority rights 
a majority of middleground afrikaners will accept the change 
grudgingly but theyll accept it he said it will be 
traumatic for some but its in fashion that will take them a 
long way 
other signs of the gradual softening of apartheid are in the 
blacks themselves 
many have overcome immense economic and educational handicaps to 
form a vast reservoir of professional and political talent 
one is cyril dlova 35 
the son of a bank messenger he now is the personnel director 
for the south african subsidiary of a us corporation lives in 
the welloff whites only johannesburg suburb of sandton and 
sends his daughter to a private multiracial school 
officially the only blacks allowed to reside in sandton are 
livein servants but dlova says hes encountered no problems in 
defying the now almostunenforced group areas act 
within days after we moved in my neighbors came over 
bringing a cake to welcome me my daughter swims in their pools 
he said its the way this country should be 
dlova who asked that his company not be identified so he 
wouldnt have to clear his remarks with his superiors said racial 
attitudes among white executives have changed slowly during his 10 
years with the firm 
when i came here there was a feeling of blacks cant do 
anything now they say maybe some blacks can do it we must next 
get to the stage where they believe all blacks can do it if they 
get the opportunity 
de klerk is on record as saying whites should retain the right 
to have segregated neighborhoods and schools but the government 
now allows communities the option of integrating and education 
officials recently dropped hints that at least some whitesonly 
schools could accept blacks if parents approved 
the staterun television network for years an unquestioning 
defender of apartheid now broadcasts news footage and interviews 
that suggest integration might be a good thing 
mrs lutu says the governments attitude has changed markedly in 
recent months as evidenced by official willingness to let former 
illegal squatters in her community gain ownership of property for 
the first time in their lives 
the pride theyre showing now in owning their own land you 
can see it she said before there was a feeling of despair 
they had lost dignity the army would come in and wreck their 
vehicles take away goods beat the youths now that has stopped 
the same people who used to raid us in the middle of the night are 
helping provide land and facilities for us 
many militant black leaders remain skeptical of the governments 
ultimate intentions but even anc officials now say they believe 
most whites are ready to give up on apartheid 
said thabo mbeki the ancs foreign affairs spokesman i dont 
imagine it will be terribly difficult to continue to be allies in 
building a postapartheid future if you have been allies in getting 
rid of this unwanted past 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

