<TEXT>
mystic and spiritual are not usually terms 
associated with a heavy metal band neither are introspective and 
cerebral 
but the british band the cult is an exception 
lead singer ian astbury springs from the same mold that produced 
jim morrison the late lead vocalist of the doors with his long 
inkblack hair vaulted cheekbones and penchant for wearing leather 
and snakeskin astbury looks more like an ancient medicine man than 
a rock singer 
his foil blond guitarist billy duffy grounds astburys 
otherworldliness with a hard rock perspective and balances the 
singers brooding seriousness with his own devilmaycare 
personality the band is rounded out by bassistrhythm guitarist 
jamie stewart and drummer matt sorum 
the cults first us release 1985s love kept them in the 
college radio spotlight with the meticulously arranged track she 
sells sanctuary the albums swirling psychedelic lyrics and 
jangly melodic guitar work pigeonholed the band into a genre known 
as gothic a trend started in britain in the early 80s 
by their next album electric in 1987 the bant released in england 
and europe duffy said 
we did a lot of our dirty laundry in public college 
alternative fans in america liked those recordings to us theyre 
very fledgling kind of experimental they have their moments but 
theyre not very relevant to where the cult is now 
part of the cults mystique stems from astburys interest in 
american indian myth and culture such songs as brother wolf 
sister moon from love and american horse from sonic 
temple depict not only the indians struggle with the white man 
but the folklore he created in trying to determine his own destiny 
the interest in indians was more prevalent in the earlier days 
of the band in southern death cult duffy says ians interest 
is still there but hes matured he has said im a white 
workingclass guy from the northwest of england who happens to 
personally feel very strongly an affinity for the american indian 
its not to the point of a flagflying exercise 
ians angle is that they do their own thing they exist they 
have their own dignity within themselves the last thing they need 
is some twobob rock n roll band carrying a flag for them 
duffy said the bands philosophy is simple 
the cult got together because we had the desire to make music 
together as individuals duffy said we all wanted to make a 
kind of music that no one in britain seemed to be interested in 
doing at the time 
from that we still maintain that basic desire we dig what 
we do were genuinely excited about the records we make and the 
songs we write we like to go out and play that to people and share 
it 
duffy doesnt see another style change coming down the line i 
think that thick sound that professional sound will be there but 
it will still be very human he said 
the band began its current tour of the united states and canada 
in san francisco on dec 27 
