<TEXT>
judging from tony hillermans books 
you might think hes navajo and many navajos are surprised to 
learn hes not 
thats because hillerman has captured american indian cultures 
particularly navajo as no other novelist 
in 1987 he was given a special friend of the navajo award 
to go with his edgar allan poe award for best mystery of 1973 
dance hall of the dead his last two books a thief of time 
and talking god have been best sellers and he now has a 125 
million contract with harper amp row 
his latest book coyote waits is scheduled for june just 
in time to start making his first movie hillerman has a 
threepicture deal with robert redford filming starts this summer 
on an adaptation of his 1982 novel the dark wind hillerman 
serves as consultant 
the author redford producers sarah pillsbury and midge sanford 
and film executive bonnie lee toured the reservation in a rented 
station wagon with redford driving discussing which of hillermans 
navajo police mysteries should be the first film 
dark wind in which navajo and hopi cops solve drugrelated 
murders was chosen because of its mixture of two indian cultures 
it will be directed by errol morris the thin blue line 
it seemed to me that since so many people who go to movies are 
the kind of people who think all indians are alike it would be 
good to put two quite different tribes in he said 
i had taken for granted redford was going to start with thief 
of time he wants to direct that one himself said hillerman 
leaning back against the antique pigeonhole desk he got from an old 
hotel office above is the friend of the navajo plaque and a 
framed drawing of navajo ceremonial masks 
on his left above his word processor is a map of indian 
country eastern arizona western new mexico and southern utah and 
colorado and a window overlooking a back yard terraced with old 
railroad ties and bricks 
his is a modest brick home in an average albuquerque 
neighborhood 
redford reached while filming in the dominican republic said 
he likes working with the 64yearold author 
he is very unfettered by either success or too much trouble 
around him redford said he travels his own route and at his 
own pace hes rare in that he has that wonderful sense of 
structure of storytelling and a very clear eye as to the real 
nature of the navajo 
born anthony grove hillerman on may 27 1925 in sacred heart 
okla the son of a storekeeper young tony was his high school 
class historian but never gave much thought to writing 
i kind of liked to write and i read a lot but i didnt know 
real human beings were writers he said i mean writers and 
writing were not something in the imagination of a kid growing up 
out there 
the idea took seed when a wounded hillerman returned on 
convalescent furlough from france during world war ii a land mine 
explosion had shattered his left leg and severely burned his left 
eye the leg still bothers him sometimes and he never regained 
full use of the eye 
beatrice stahl a feature writer for the daily oklahoman in 
oklahoma city had done a story based on hillermans letters home 
and now she wanted to interview him so i went down there and 
talked to her she told me i ought to be a writer 
he took her advice and studied journalism at the university of 
oklahoma he graduated amid a flood of wardelayed students in 
1948 and he couldnt find a job on a newspaper 
so i took a job with an advertising agency writing radio 
commercials it was just a tryout job doing ads for cains better 
coffee and purina pig chow he said 
at oklahoma he met his wife marie they now have six grown 
children 
he also took a job driving a truck hauling oil field supplies 
one stop was the navajo reservation in new mexico on one run he 
saw navajos on horseback in ceremonial attire for the enemy way a 
soulcleansing ritual that follows combat they too were 
returning veterans 
of course most of them served in the pacific he said 
something about them touched him and he never forgot from then 
on he said new mexico was his ultimate destination 
when hillerman got the chance to be bureau manager for united 
press international in santa fe he grabbed it he served as 
executive editor of the new mexican in santa fe after leaving the 
wire service 
during the santa fe stint he covered a story in which a 
jicarilla apache police officer was shot to death the 
investigation showed the fallen officer had coolly shifted his 
revolver from his wounded arm to his good hand and had shot one of 
his assailants before dying the indian was the model for navajo 
detective lt joe leaphorn mainstay of hillermans novels 
hillerman had sold some nonfiction through a new york agent 
when he offered her the manuscript in the late 1960s for his first 
leaphorn novel the blessing way she told him just get rid 
of all the indian stuff 
probably it was fairly good advice but it wasnt what i 
wanted to do he said an editor at harper amp row liked it indian 
stuff and all it was published in 1970 
navajos tell hillerman they like his books because theyre true 
to navajo culture and the navajos come out winners in fact he 
said many navajos express surprise upon learning hes not a navajo 
himself 
i run into that when i sign books around the reservation he 
said 
despite the mystery witchcraft and violence of his books 
hillerman bristles at any suggestion the reservation might be a 
dangerous place 
in the navajo culture all goals are toward harmony being 
peaceful working together people who turn against this are the 
worst kind of people he said when asked to define a navajo witch 
what does he like most about the navajo 
i like their emphasis on taking care of the family he said 
i like the dignity they give their women i like their attitude 
about material possessions they just dont attach any importance 
to them theres the idea that if you own too much you probably 
arent taking care of your family 
i like the emphasis they have on beauty aesthetics so many 
navajos seem to have a good eye for the sunset the pleasing design 
i like their sense of humor their stoic endurance of whatever 
comes down they endure 
</TEXT>
