<TEXT>
researchers are looking into how well the 
elderly adjust in the sun belt without the support of family and 
friends they left behind in the north 
the case western reserve university study tracks 800 people over 
75 who moved from northern cities to a clearwater fla retirement 
community 
we think the results would help health care professionals to 
see what the needs of old people are who have relocated and to 
counsel people as they plan relocation said eva kahana who 
chairs the sociology department and directs the study 
it would also help counsel families it would either help 
reassure them that the social support networks that people develop 
in these communities are adequate or what kind of help is 
available we would be able to develop guidelines for doctors 
social workers and families in having a more realistic picture of 
what to expect 
her study is a spinoff of a 1984 case western survey in which 
150 people in their 60s or early 70s who had just moved to florida 
were asked how stressful the move was and how they were faring 
researchers followed them for a year 
ms kahana said researchers found that the majority were 
satisfied with their choice that they didnt miss very much their 
home communities or the people they had left 
the question that remains is whether those findings continue 
as they get older she said 
for the new study field workers are interviewing people over 75 
in the clearwater community which ms kahana would not identify 
the 800 interviews should be finished by the end of april 
residents are asked about lifestyle mental and physical health 
and longdistance communication with family and friends they also 
are asked to what extent paid helpers or agencies are used to get 
groceries clean houses do yardwork or help them meet appointments 
or activities 
researchers will keep in touch with the same people for eight 
years 
we should not make the inference that relocation to the 
sun belt is good for people period ms kahana said it may be 
that in the short run it works out very positively but once they 
become frail they would be missing the natural supports of the 
family 
but one of our hypotheses is that the neighbors and friends 
in the new community take on the role of family members 
we dont know the extent to which elderly people can make deep 
friendships late in life were going to be looking in depth at 
that how friends and neighbors help one another 
in 1970 about 53000 ohioans aged 60 and over left ohio that 
jumped to 86000 in 1980 the last year for which the census bureau 
has figures said charles longino associate director of the center 
of adult development and aging at the university of miami at coral 
gables fla 
in 1980 44 percent of the 86000 moved to florida ten years 
earlier 36 percent went to florida california drew 8 percent in 
1980 and 11 percent in 1970 
of the countrys 226 million people in 1980 356 million were 
at least 65 and about 5 percent of that age group moved out of 
their states longino said florida drew more of the elderly than 
any other state with about 437000 people in 1980 
