<TEXT>
is it plausible that plants like people do 
better in congenial settings and that insect pests avoid 
distasteful things concede the possibility and you really should 
try companion or repellent planting 
does it work 
ive come to believe in it absolutely says jim johnson of 
phoenix president of the arizona herb association i havent 
used chemical pesticides in my garden for five years and im 
convinced plants grow best among their friends 
jane haynes of suburban fountain hills another expert on herbs 
says she reacted with enthusiasm when first hearing of the idea 20 
or 25 years ago but im still not satisfied it happens that way 
much as id like to 
one thing is sure collegetrained horticulturists no longer 
burst into gales of laughter when people say things like they never 
plant peas near onions or they believe marigolds deter certain 
pests and basil helps tomatoes grow definitive scientific studies 
are in their infancy however 
in my landscape i try to avoid chemicals but dont hesitate to 
use them if natural forces seem to be losing or if theres no 
known natural control and my records over the years seem to show 
some plants do better or worse near others 
the rodale folks in emmaus pa publishers of organic gardening 
magazine began popularizing the companionrepellent theory a 
couple decades ago 
details are spelled out in the encyclopedia of natural insect 
and disease control published in 1984 by rodale press and 
available in most bookstores 2495 hardcover even if you 
question the concept this is an excellent reference on how to work 
with nature and minimize toxic chemicals 
author roger p yepsen jr suggests the benefits of companion 
planting may be due to the increased health of vegetables growing 
near their friends insects typically pass by healthy plants 
preferring to pick on weak or sick plants 
why are companionate plantings healthier yepsen continues 
perhaps because the plants make complementary demands on the 
environment for instance the compatibility of celery and leek can 
be traced to the uprightgrowing leek enjoying the room and light 
near the bushy celery plant or the roots of two friendly plants 
may occupy different strata of the soil as do those of swiss chard 
and beans 
the book lists many repellent plantings such as rosemary vs 
snails and slugs spearmint vs ants and garlic vs aphids 
garlic it says helps out no matter where you plant it and 
keeps the potato bugs bean beetles and stem borers from achieving 
pest status but yepsens main thrust is that a delicate balance of 
life forms exists in any landscape and troubles develop when you 
upset the balance between pests and beneficial forces 
to illustrate how the world changes i recall an incident 
involving my college professor in agricultural pest control he was 
an imposing physical specimen a former pro football end one day a 
little bug invaded his demonstration garden ohmygod a bug he 
cried he literally shook as he drenched it with ddt a pesticide 
outlawed a decade or so later 
johnson believes insects follow smells a cabbage worm is 
attracted by the scent of cabbage and a tomato worm by the scent of 
tomatoes for example 
so he plants garlic and other members of the onion family 
throughout his garden and flower beds to confuse insects and uses 
various herbs around specific plants 
while i dont grow a lot of tomatoes maybe a halfdozen 
plants i havent had a tomato worm in five years by planting a 
lot of garlic cloves the worst that can happen is ill have a lot 
of nice garlic he says 
johnson also grows basil next to the tomatoes reasoning they 
like each other what about garlic and roses 
i think roses like garlic better than garlic likes roses he 
says but no plants seem to like fennel although bees seem to 
love it since i want to draw bees for pollination i grow fennel 
but plant it away from everything else 
haynes says she has tried to keep track of companion plantings 
for about 20 years and remains unconvinced 
theres so many possible variants i dont see any big 
differences take planting marigolds to deter nematodes how do you 
know for sure you have nematodes or that marigolds did any good 
shes sure however that the moon influences gardening she 
propagates her herbs by inserting cuttings in water 
i get roots more quickly four to five days quicker before a 
full moon than after one and they seem to be much stronger too 
moon gardening has been around for generations of course many 
believers will not plant or prune or even turn the soil without 
checking an almanac the theory is that the moons gravitational 
pull influences fluids in plants just as it does the ocean tides 
</TEXT>
