more than 10 million the new york times said in wednesdays 
editions 
drexel spokesman steven anreder declined to comment on the size 
of individual bonuses the payments were determined last year and 
were part of running the firms business the times quoted anreder 
as saying 
if we didnt have bonuses we wouldnt have had anybody 
working for us he said 
representatives of drexels creditors plan to examine the 
bonuses to determine if they could be recovered during bankruptcy 
proceedings the times reported 
us trustee harold jones who is supervising the bankruptcy 
case has set an organizational meeting for the creditors for feb 
27 in new york 
the chapter 11 filing allows drexel to manage with the judges 
approval its dismantling creditors could seek to force drexel to 
liquidate under chapter 7 where the companys control over its 
dissolution would be sharply reduced 
people are going to be considering the pluses and minuses of 
chapter 11 vs chapter 7 said margaret shearer deputy general 
counsel of ambase corp whose home capital services inc 
subsidiary is the second largest unsecured creditor at 427 
million thats a major issue 
schopf said creditors want to make sure drexel is receiving fair 
value for any asset sales and transfers and to determine whether 
drexel insiders have benefitted from them 
drexel attorney alan miller said the subsidiaries want to get as 
much as possible from asset sales because unsecured creditors will 
have priority in the bankruptcy over employees 54 percent stake in 
the parent company 
the people who are here at drexel who are winding down the 
business of the subsidiaries have a vital economic interest in the 
success of the winddown miller said 
drexel said tuesday it had liquidated 82 percent of its 
securities inventory selling all but 86 billion out of 474 
billion in holdings the sales include government highgrade 
corporate mortgagebacked municipal and junk bonds as well as 
equity and convertible securities 
our objective was to maximize the asset values for creditors 
and shareholders and it could only be done through an effective 
liquidation accomplished at market prices drexel said in a 
statement 
in its filing drexel listed more than 2000 total creditors 
assets of 37 billion and liabilities of 289 billion 
drexel last week fired most of its 5300 employees spokesman 
steven anreder said tuesday about 1700 workers remained to finish 
winding down the firms operations employees also are being 
allowed to use drexels offices temporarily to search for new jobs 
creditors may have a difficult time quickly gaining details 
about the assets of drexels parent us bankruptcy judge howard 
buschman iii last week gave the company a 90day extension to file 
a comprehensive account of assets and liabilities 
first city filed motions tuesday requesting the judge to 
reconsider the 90day extension and to compel an examination of 
drexels assets schopf said buschman scheduled a march 1 hearing 
to consider the motions schopf added 
it seems to me we should get whatever information is available 
