<TEXT>
two electronic funds transfer systems that 
handle more than 1 trillion daily in interbank transactions need 
better security measures to guard against fraud or computer mishap 
a congressional study has concluded 
the study by the general accounting office called for beefedup 
security measures for the electronic funds transfer systems used by 
the federal reserve system and most of the nations banks fedwire 
and the clearing house interbank payments system or chips 
a related gao study noted that internal security weaknesses of 
stock exchange computer systems raise risks of sabotage that 
could literally bring securities trading to a halt even though 
the systems are well protected against attack by outsiders 
the gao found a number of internal control weaknesses at the 
computer centers of the nations two major stock exchanges and the 
national association of securities dealers which oversees the 
overthecounter market 
both studies were requested by rep edward j markey dmass 
chairman of the house energy and commerce committees subcommittee 
on finance which was to conduct a hearing today on computer 
security in the financial markets 
the banking study found that there have not been any reported 
incidents of fraudulent electronic funds transfers over the systems 
by the employees who operate or oversee them however the results 
of our review of the security measures in place to protect these 
systems from misuse have not been satisfying 
the report said it found 17 fedwire control weaknesses at the 
four federal reserve banks investigators visited in new york 
chicago dallas and san francisco weaknesses ranged from 
inadequate surveillance by cameras or motion sensors in critical 
processing areas to inadequate control of software that allows 
access to fedwire 
fedwire is the primary wholesale electronic funds transfer 
system used by the banking community to handle the payments banks 
make to each other within the united states in 1988 fedwire 
served over 11000 depository institutions and government agencies 
and processed transactions valued at 253 trillion 
the computer security report said officials at the new york 
stock exchange the american stock exchange the nasd and the 
securities industry automation corporation siac a jointlyowned 
subsidiary of both exchanges that operates computerized systems 
have implemented a wide range of security controls that protect 
their systems from the external threat of a hacker or virus attack 
and as a result the risk of such a threat is relatively low 
a hacker is a computer tinkerer who tries to gain access to 
computer systems without authorization a virus is a renegade 
program that once placed into a computer system can reproduce and 
spread among computer systems disrupting or destroying computer 
services 
but the most significant threat of potential tampering comes 
from the employees who have access to the exchange and nasd 
computer systems said the report 
the report recommended the sec periodically conduct or oversee 
independent assessments of the exchanges and nasds computer 
security programs develop written information security plans and 
policies and conduct periodic risk analyses 
in november the sec issued a policy statement asking exchanges 
and the nasd to review their computer systems periodically and 
conduct studies to assess their capacity and vulnerability 
the study found 10 security weaknesses at nasd including 
computer center staff performing tasks beyond their normal 
responsibility 
at the siac the study found three security weaknesses 
including contingency planning in the event of a computer virus 
attack 
the american stock exchange had no immediate comment tuesday 
evening a spokeswoman for the new york stock exchange sharon 
gamsin said the big board had not seen the gao report and would 
not comment until it had reviewed it 
charles justice vice president for automation at the nasd said 
some of the gao criticisms already had been addressed 
we agreed essentially that steps could be taken and we did 
take them he said they were taking a federal standard and 
were trying to apply it to a nonfederal operation we were kind of 
in technical violation but we simply dont follow that standard in 
terms of a substantive violation i dont think there was anything 
that was serious 
a fed spokesman said the agencys comments would come in hearing 
testimony by fed governor wayne d angell 
</TEXT>
