experts said the deal announced tuesday is one of the first in 
which japanese technological expertise will flow into the united 
states rather than vice versa the deal also would give sony its 
first us chipmaking outpost 
under the agreement sony will take over two advanced micro 
devices factories in san antonio and hire about 650 amd workers 
the tokyobased company plans to refurbish one nowidle production 
line and use it to make advanced memory chips known as static 
random access memory chips or srams 
meanwhile amd will continue receiving the chip output of the 
other plant and its engineers will study how sony runs the 
refurbished factory 
you cannot succeed in this business if you are not in control 
of your production processes said jerry sanders amds chief 
executive 
amd with 11 billion in sales is the nations fifthlargest 
semiconductor maker about equal in size to sonys chip business 
for the past five years the two companies have collaborated on the 
development of new sram products 
the new agreement is not aimed so much at learning manufacturing 
technology but at learning how japanese companies use it sanders 
said those companies are able to get more chips with fewer defects 
from plants similar to those used in the united states 
amd has sent engineers to japan to study sonys techniques but 
the company said it expects to learn more by applying those methods 
alongside sonys engineers 
sony will benefit from the deal by acquiring the work force and 
management at the san antonio plans while amd will receive both 
cash and manufacturing expertise said david angel vice president 
of semiconductor research at dataquest inc in san jose 
others said that while the agreement means the sale of another 
american asset to the japanese amd saved us jobs and probably 
will improve its profitability 
sanders also expected the two companies to complete an 
additional agreement to develop a new complementary metaloxide 
semiconductor process that he said could double the number of 
circuits that can be put on a piece of silicon 
