<DOCNO> AP900221-0271 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court today upheld a federal law 
that allows abandoned rail lines to be used for nature trails 
the court in a case from vermont unanimously rejected 
arguments that the 1983 law known as the railstotrails act 
unconstitutionally deprives property owners of use of their land 
without just compensation 
justice william j brennan writing for the court said a 
separate federal law permits property owners to file a claim 
against the government to determine whether they are entitled to 
compensation 
brennan also said the railstotrails law is a legitimate 
exercise of congressional power aimed at encouraging the 
development of additional recreational trails 
the ruling could affect a large number of property owners some 
10000 miles of railroad rightsofway have been abandoned in the 
united states since 1985 
in other action the court 
limited the office of management and budgets power to order 
changes in federal jobsafety rules 
the court ruled 72 that the omb in trying to reduce paperwork 
for private businesses may not block or change rules made by other 
government agencies 
upheld federal regulations aimed at saving the government time 
and money when it mistakenly overpays some social security 
recipients 
the justices voting 54 in a case from colorado said the rules 
are a reasonable interpretation of the social security act the 
court rejected arguments that needy recipients could suffer undue 
hardship 
reinstated a 61 million award against the arthur young amp co 
accounting firm won by investors in the farmers cooperative of 
arkansas and oklahoma 
the justices by a 54 vote ruled that the financial notes held 
by the coops investors are securities as defined by federal 
law 
a federal appeals court had thrown out the award after ruling 
that the notes were not securities todays decision reversed that 
ruling 
the railstotrails law was challenged by j paul and patricia 
preseault who claim they own land on a rightofway abandoned by 
vermont railroad inc that claim is disputed by vermont officials 
who say the state owns the land 
the railroad discontinued service in 1975 over a 17mile 
stretch of its north burlington branch rail line in chittenden 
county vt 
if the preseaults own the disputed property they have a right 
under vermont law to use the land once rail service is discontinued 
and the railways easement automatically expires 
but the federal law an amended version of the earlier national 
trails system act allows for railroad rightsofway to be 
maintained for possible future railroad use while the land is 
converted at least temporarily to nature trails 
this practice known as rail banking is at the heart of the 
case decided today 
vermont entered into a lease with the city of burlington that 
allows the city to maintain the rightofway as a trail while 
preserving it for possible rail use 
citing the statecity agreement the interstate comerce 
commission rejected the preseaults bid to have the rail line 
declared officially abandoned 
the preseaults said the railbanking provisions are a sham aimed 
at disguising the true purpose of the federal law preventing 
reversion of rightsofway to property owners after abandonment 
the couple said the railbanking procedure is intended to 
disguise the fact that the rail lines have been abandoned 
brennan rejected that argument 
the law is not invalid merely because more draconian measures 
such as a program of mandatory conversions or a prohibition of 
all abandonments might advance more completely the railbanking 
purpose he said the history of congressional attempts to 
address the problem of rail abanondonments provides sufficient 
reason to defer to congress he added 
the preseaults said the 1983 law violates the constitutions 
fifth amendment which bars the taking of private property without 
just compensation and also said it interferes unlawfully with 
interstate commerce 
the case is preseault vs icc 881076 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

