<TEXT>
into that already stuffed file of lessons we 
should have learned but didnt you may drop the latest data on 
oil imports which in january reached the highest level in 12 years 
not only are imports rising domestic production also is 
falling and is now lower than it was two decades ago 
petroleum imports in january reached 91 million barrels a day 
or more than half what is consumed in the united states a nation 
that has enormous fuel reserves available 
at the same time domestic crude oil production dropped in 
january to just 74 million barrels a day more than 5 percent 
lower than a year earlier and 20 percent lower than levels of about 
four years ago 
foreign oil sources are being relied upon more each year 
domestic sources less each year a remarkable trend in terms of 
history geography economics and national security among them 
the economic destruction in the form of inflation soaring 
interest rates and reduced domestic output that resulted from the 
oil embargo of the 1970s 
a vow by americans in all walks of life from the individual 
car owner and homeowner to the white house never again to be 
caught short of oil because of foreign limitations on supply 
the balance of payments problem oil imports probably account 
for as much as 50 billion of the gap between imports and exports 
a successful conservation effort by the american people one 
that seemingly could have been maintained almost effortlessly 
an assured market for domestic production made possible by the 
longterm growth of the american economy 
the demonstrated ingenuity of americans in developing more 
fuelefficient products to say nothing about alternative sources 
of energy 
incredibly there is little observable effort being made to 
rectify the situation by the federal government little mention of 
the situation is made in the detailed forecasts of economists 
on the edge of crisis the oil problem is discussed like the 
weather the assumption being that tomorrow no matter what anyone 
does there will be oil to burn as surely as there will be a sky up 
above 
the attitude is similar to that which preceded the crises of the 
1970s america suggests economist edward yardeni one of a 
relative few economists who include the problem in their analyses 
is as vulnerable now as then 
the impact of any increase in the price of oil or shortage in 
supplies is almost instantaneous and the reminder is as recent as 
now when oil prices still reflect the unexpectedly severe cold of 
december 
you cannot run factories homes schools or churches without 
fuel you cannot distribute food you cannot draw water in high 
buildings in fact without fuel you cannot even breath in some 
you cannot see in the night 
it is one of the more awesome items in the file of lessons we 
should have learned but didnt because in these modern times we 
couldnt live a day without it 
more awesome is that the problem can be ignored by so many at 
so many levels of society 
