<TEXT>
drexel burnham lambert creditors said wednesday 
they will seek a bankruptcy court investigation of up to 350 
million in yearend bonuses paid shortly before the firms collapse 
a drexel spokesman said the payments were set in december and 
were not made with any knowledge the firm would go out of business 
drexels parent company filed for bankruptcy court protection last 
week 
were talking about bonus payments so large they arguably put 
drexel into bankruptcy said william g schopf jr general 
counsel of first city bancorp of texas inc which is owed 25 
million if thats true it would be something we would seek to 
reverse if possible 
schopf and other creditors said they would seek details about 
the payments from drexel executives during bankruptcy court 
proceedings 
also rep edward j markey dmass chairman of the house 
energy and commerce committees finance subcomittee said the panel 
planned to look into the bonus payments in the coming weeks 
us bankruptcy judge howard buschman late tuesday granted first 
city a hearing on its motion seeking to force drexel to detail 
asset sales made in the liquidation of the brokerage subsidiary 
drexel burnham lambert inc 
drexel has sold nearly 40 billion in securities positions as 
well as other assets in its dismantling the firm still is trying 
to liquidate about 18 percent of its portfolio and sell equipment 
furniture and other assets 
the creditors could face difficulties because the securities 
subsidiary is not covered by the bankruptcy filing but they said 
they would seek to investigate the payments because of their size 
and timing 
it gives rise to concern as does any large transfer made 
shortly prior to the bankruptcy filing said wayne davis an 
attorney with a new york law firm representing several large 
creditors 
creditors may seek to recover payments made outside the normal 
course of business for up to 90 days before a bankruptcy filing 
the period stretches to one year for payments to company insiders 
sources said the bonuses totaled between 300 million and 350 
million but drexel spokesman steven anreder said the size of most 
of the cash payouts was determined in december before the firms 
financial problems became critical 
he said one executive chose to take his entire bonus in drexel 
stock the value of which was wiped out by the firms demise 
there was no sense of foreboding here at all anreder said 
it was only in the last week and a half that things were 
difficult but even then no one thought the firm would go under 
anreder said the bonuses were paid in december and early 
january the size of some of the payments was determined in early 
1989 he said 
we did what we believed we had to do competitively and it was 
within both the norms of what the longstanding practice had been at 
the firm and within the norms of the industry anreder said 
drexel insiders said some individual bonuses exceeded 10 
million with reports being circulated of payouts approaching 20 
million they contended the firm could have slashed its bonuses 
long regarded as among the industrys most excessive to save 
money the firm lost about 40 million in 1989 
they also said the payouts raised questions about managements 
handling of the firms deteriorating financial condition in the 
months leading up to the bankruptcy filing 
anreder said drexel reduced 1989 bonuses but he did not specify 
by how much most wall street firms cut the payouts by up to 20 
percent last year because of a severe securities industry business 
slowdown 
drexels parent sought bankruptcy protection feb 13 after it 
defaulted on 100 million in shortterm loans and banks refused to 
extend credit the firm had relied on such loans to sustain its 
capital base 
anreder said drexel aware of its financial problems late last 
year moved to shore up its standing through employee payments 
requiring executives making more that 200000 a year to take up to 
18 percent of their salary in company securities 
