griffins resorts casino hotel in atlantic city despite its 
bankruptcy proceedings 
the mere filing of a chapter 11 action does not in and of 
itself warrant a conclusion that a company lacks financial 
stability acting commission chairwoman valerie armstrong said 
the bankruptcy action is but one albeit significant factor 
she said resorts had shown during commission hearings last week 
it could become financially stable within the twoyear license 
period under a flat growth scenario 
resorts filed for bankruptcy protection from creditors in 
federal court in camden last november it is seeking approval for a 
reorganization plan from creditors and a federal bankruptcy judge 
resorts last month won 143 million from gamblers an 11 
percent drop from the 161 million registered in january 1989 
according to commission figures the casinos win for all of 1989 
dropped 64 percent to 2274 million compared to the previous year 
win is the amount of money gamblers lose and does not take into 
account expenses it is not profit 
under the flat growth forecast resorts will post a 500000 
cash deficit at the end of 1990 because of an extensive 
refurbishing program the commission said in its unanimous ruling 
the commission imposed conditions recommended by the division of 
gaming enforcement that resorts file monthly balance sheets income 
statements and statements of cash flow and working capital 
resorts officials also must advise regulators on a monthly basis 
of significant deviations from financial projections and from prior 
financial performance 
but the commission stopped short of requiring the casino to 
report daily or weekly or to set a specific cash balance that would 
trigger the imposition of restricted accounts to ensure that wages 
taxes and progressive jackpots are paid 
