northrop corp the builder of the b2 
bomber said it lost 166 million in the fourth quarter and 635 
million in 1989 largely because of high costs on fixedprice 
research and development contracts with the government 
the fixedprice accords have been costly for many aerospace 
giants mcdonnell douglas corp whose fourthquarter profits fell 
58 percent has run behind schedule in developing the c17 cargo 
plane and t45 navy training jet and lockheed corp showed about 
300 million in pretax fourthquarter losses because of unforeseen 
changes on a new submarinehunting plane 
northrop took a total of 240 million in writeoffs for such 
development losses in 1989 with 28 million of that in the fourth 
quarter about 81 million of the writeoffs were on development of 
radarjamming equipment and another 159 million on classified 
programs in northrops missiles and unmanned vehicles segment 
since early 1988 northrop has refused to accept fixedprice 
development contracts lockheed and rockwell international corp 
also refuse to do so saying the risk of unforeseen expenses is too 
great during the initial development of complicated programs for 
the military 
for the octoberdecember quarter northrop lost 166 million 
or 35 cents a share compared with a loss of 861 million 183 a 
share in the same period of 1988 sales plunged 232 percent to 
133 billion from 173 billion 
for the full year northrop lost 635 million or 135 a 
share compared with earnings of 1042 million or 222 a share 
in 1988 the 1988 profit figure included a favorable onetime tax 
adjustment of 1351 million sales fell 95 percent last year to 
525 billion from 58 billion in 1988 
separately northrop said it had completed the previously 
announced sale of twin office towers in century city that house its 
headquarters for 218 million in cash northrop whose total debt 
had been 12 billion used the proceeds to reduce its shortterm 
debt to 424 million the company is leasing back its headquarters 
space 
the sale yielded a pretax gain of 136 million of which 102 
million will be recognized in 1990 and the rest spread over the 
next 10 years aftertax earnings for the first quarter of 1990 
will benefit by 67 million or 142 a share the company said 
fourthquarter revenues fell in the aircraft segment as 
development work on the b2 wound down and fewer main body 
assemblies were delivered for the fa18 fighter 
sales also fell in the electronics segment where deliveries of 
guidance systems for the mx missile fell and in the missiles and 
unmanned vehicles segment the latter decline stemmed from an 
accounting change for work on a classified contract causing a 120 
million reduction in quarterly sales 
for the full year the effect of the fourthquarter charges was 
partially offset by higher revenues from startup of b2 production 
and increased delivery of parts for the boeing 747 jetliner 
northrop said its business backlog stood at 56 billion at the 
end of 1989 compared with 49 billion at the end of 1988 kent 
kresa the company chairman has predicted 1990 sales will stay at 
about the same level as in 1989 
