<TEXT>
state environmental officials complained 
wednesday that senate and white house negotiations are weakening a 
proposed clean air bill so much that many urban areas would not be 
able to meet the air quality standards 
the officials from 13 states many of which are plagued with 
some of the worst urban smog problems in the country criticized 
the closeddoor dealmaking and urged senate leaders to bring the 
measure to the senate floor where it can be openly debated 
among the state officials who accused the senate and 
administration negotiators of weakening the senate bill were those 
responsible for air pollution controls in southern california and 
the new york city area two regions facing the most serious smog 
problems 
under the compromises already tentatively agreed to in the 
private senate negotiations we would not be able to obtain 
healthy air in southern california said norton younglove 
chairman of the south coast air quality management district in 
california 
thomas joring new york state commissioner of environmental 
conservation said some of the provisions worked out in the private 
talks would make the new air pollution control law weaker than 
current law especially as it applies to curbing urban smog 
the criticism came as senate leaders and the bush adminstration 
continued the closeddoor discussions for a third week in hopes of 
crafting a bill that would have enough support to avoid a 
contentuous debate and possible filibuster on the senate floor 
senate majority leader george mitchell said he hoped to conclude 
by the end of the week the private discussions on the bill which 
would revise federal air pollution controls for the first time in 
13 years 
mitchell said he expects plenty of debate on the senate 
floor once the private discussions are completed 
while the talks have reached tentative agreements on some parts 
of the bill such as curbs on acid rain major differences remained 
over how to reduce pollution for automobiles 
the senate bill calls for a second round of tailpipe controls 
while the administration says thats too expensive and favors using 
cleaner motor fuels in the most polluted areas of the country such 
as los angeles and the northeast 
but the state pollution control officials focused their 
criticism on areas where the negotiators already have reached 
agreement 
among the areas of concern were compromises that would no 
longer require the federal government to impose a smog cleanup plan 
if local officials are unwilling or unable to do so that would 
exempt small industrial polluters from urban smog controls reduce 
the geographic areas that would be covered under urban air cleanup 
programs 
the pollution cleanup program envisioned by this senatebush 
administration deal will not work in practice the state 
officials said in a statement 
the group included air pollution control officials from the 
states of california oregon washington nevada colorado 
delaware new jersey new york rhode island massachusetts new 
hampshire vermont and maine 
meanwhile a group of environmental organizations blamed white 
house chief of staff john sununu for the administrations stand on 
the clean air bill claiming that sununu was undercutting the 
presidents environmental policies 
the groups including the national wildlife federation national 
audubon society and the natural resources defense council asked to 
meet with bush to discuss their environmental concerns including 
those involving the clean air bill negotiations 
marlin fitzwater the presidents spokesman said sununu 
ensures that all points of view are heard and that is a role that 
he has played with regard to environmental policies 
and the president has made the decisions on environmental 
policies they represent his point of view and his priorities 
fitzwater continued and environmnental groups by the same 
token represent interest groups and pressure groups and it is 
their job to keep the pressure on theyre doing it the governors 
doing his job i dont see any real difficulty here 
 
