<TEXT>
oregons largest thrift institution benj 
franklin federal savings and loan association was seized wednesday 
by regulators who said it failed to meet the stringent financial 
standards of the new savings and loan law 
the resolution trust corp created last august to dispose of 
failed sampls took control of the portland institution which has 
about 5 billion in assets after the office of thrift supervision 
said franklin was operating in an unsafe and unsound condition 
franklin largely because of the new capital standards 106 
million in the red at the end of november according to ed 
headlund deputy district director of the thrift offices seattle 
office 
that was after an accounting break of about 280 million known 
as supervisory goodwill was removed from its books it had booked 
most of the goodwill as a result of its 1982 acquisition of 
equitable savings and loan which it took over at regulators 
request 
goodwill is usually the difference between the purchase price of 
an asset and its real value 
the sampl bill last august revoked the accounting break for 
franklin and scores of other sampls the law now requires 
institutions to hold tangible capital of 150 for every 100 of 
assets and does not permit them to count good will in the 150 
also franklin suffered from problems in the oregon real estate 
market that surfaced several years earlier according to headlund 
in an attempt to pull out of its problems franklin in october 
announced a costcutting program that included layoffs and the sale 
of its commercial lending operation 
kevin shields a portlandbased spokesman for the resolution 
trust corp said the corporation will try to sell franklin to or 
merge it with another savings and loan 
but that wont happen quickly he said estimating it would 
take six months before buyers might be sought 
franklin chief executive officer g dale weight will be on paid 
leave he said 
unlike many failed sampls it did not invest heavily in commercial 
real estate or in securities such as junk bonds about 80 percent 
of its holdings were residential mortgages 
franklin is the largest of oregons 12 thrifts at the end of 
september it was the 41st largest sampl in the nation according 
sheshunoff information services inc an austin texas consulting 
firm in addition to oregon it operated branches in idaho and 
washington state 
regulators said franklin would maintain normal business hours 
and stressed that all deposits up to the 100000 insurance limit 
are guaranteed it had 32 billion in deposits in 448612 accounts 
its takeover brings the number of sampls under government 
management to 320 
