drexel burnham lambert inc paid bonuses 
totalling hundreds of millions of dollars to its executives just 
weeks before its parent company filed for bankruptcy protection a 
newspaper reported 
the payments totalled as much as 350 million since december 
the new york times said in wednesdays editions citing wall street 
executives 
yearend bonuses are standard practice on wall street although 
drexel has been known for paying huge bonuses the newspaper said 
several people inside the firm said some top executives received 
bonuses of more than 10 million two to three weeks before drexels 
collapse the times reported 
drexel spokesman steven anreder declined to comment on the size 
of individual bonuses the bonuses were determined last year and 
were part of running the firms business the times quoted anreder 
as saying 
if we didnt have bonuses we wouldnt have had anybody 
working for us he said 
representatives of drexels creditors told the times they would 
examine the bonus payments to determine if they could be recovered 
as part of the chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings 
creditors may face a hurdle in trying to recover any bonuses 
because drexels securities subsidiary which paid the bonuses 
wasnt covered by the parent firms bankruptcy filing 
federal regulations prevent securities firms from filing for 
bankruptcy nevertheless drexels securities arm already has sold 
most of its nearly 50 billion in securities and the operationg 
will be liquidated as a result of the parent companys bankruptcy 
filing officials at the firm have said 
